{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"78c5c484-56c1-4141-9443-eb8e3c1cb710","content":"Since you already have the dump file collected, here's how to analyze it:\n\n**Using `dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n```bash\n# Install if needed\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze your-app.dmp\n```\n\nKey SOS commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `pe` / `printexception` | Show the last exception |\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrthreads` | List all managed threads |\n| `dso` | Dump stack objects |\n| `gcroot <addr>` | Find what's keeping an object alive |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap summary (for memory issues) |\n\n**Typical workflow to find crash root cause:**\n1. `pe` — check if there's an unhandled exception\n2. `clrthreads` — find the faulting thread\n3. `setthread <id>` → `clrstack` — inspect its stack\n4. `pe -nested` — see inner exceptions\n\n**On Windows**, you can also use **WinDbg** with the SOS extension for richer analysis.\n\nWould you like me to walk you through running any of these commands on your dump file?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ef5ca165-5feb-472a-8f15-5f54dbd24f50","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a .dmp crash dump file from a .NET application and wants to analyze it. Let me help them with this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description says it's for **configuring and collecting** crash dumps, NOT for analyzing them. It explicitly says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze.\"\n\nSo the `dump-collect` skill is not appropriate here. Let me help the user directly with guidance on analyzing the dump.\n\nI should provide guidance on how to analyze a .NET crash dump using tools like `dotnet-dump analyze`, `lldb`, or WinDbg. \n\nI'll walk them through the practical steps for analyzing their dump 